{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645177"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.05,0,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114552"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96553"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9948"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25165"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114552"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory cilia are essential components of the mucociliary clearance system in the airways. These microscopic hair-like projections extend from the surface of respiratory epithelial cells. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal movement pattern of respiratory cilia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fast power stroke followed by slow recovery stroke","Continuous clockwise rotation","Simultaneous bidirectional movement","Slow power stroke followed by fast recovery stroke","Random multidirectional beating"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory cilia move in a coordinated two-phase pattern: the \u003Cstrong\u003Efast power stroke\u003C/strong\u003E extends the cilium fully upward and forward to contact the mucus layer, followed by a \u003Cstrong\u003Eslow recovery stroke\u003C/strong\u003E where the cilium returns to its starting position while bent to minimize mucus contact. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern differs from \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinuous clockwise rotation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esimultaneous bidirectional movement\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom multidirectional beating\u003C/strong\u003E, which would be ineffective for directional mucus transport. The power stroke must be fast rather than slow to effectively propel mucus towards the oropharynx at 12-15 beats per second.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis specific movement pattern is crucial for effective mucociliary clearance. During the power stroke, the extended cilia tips contact and push the mucus layer, while during the recovery stroke, the bent cilia move back through the watery periciliary layer without disrupting the mucus above. This coordinated movement, multiplied across millions of cilia, creates a continuous conveyor belt effect that moves mucus and trapped particles at a rate of approximately 5-20 mm per minute towards the oropharynx for elimination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respiratory cilia beat in a coordinated two-phase pattern with a fast power stroke and slow recovery stroke.","The ciliary beat frequency in healthy respiratory epithelium is 12-15 Hz at body temperature.","Mucociliary clearance depends on properly functioning respiratory cilia to move mucus and trapped particles towards the oropharynx."],"references":["West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 1; pg. 10.","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96553"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96553"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T15:40:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T15:40:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114552"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"